summary_points: 1. At Booking Holdings Inc.'s 2025 Annual Meeting on June 3, 2025, a stockholder proposal to modify the company's special meeting threshold was not approved, with 13,464,542 votes for and 14,018,112 votes against.
2.  All board nominees were elected at the June 3, 2025 annual meeting; however, the number of votes against each nominee ranged from 100,462 to 1,364,317.
3. An advisory vote to approve 2024 executive compensation was approved with 24,288,898 votes for and 3,156,175 votes against.

1. On June 4, 2025, General Dynamics Corporation announced several executive promotions, including Danny Deep to Executive Vice President, Global Operations, and Jason Aiken to Executive Vice President, Combat Systems (also retaining Mission Systems).
2.  The filing reports no significant numerical comparisons related to financial performance or operational changes.
3. The executive changes are expected to improve operating performance across General Dynamics' business units.
1. GE HealthCare Technologies Inc. priced an underwritten offering of $650,000,000 in 4.800% Notes due January 15, 2031, and $850,000,000 in 5.500% Notes due June 15, 2035 on June 3, 2025.
2.  The notes are expected to be issued around June 9, 2025.
3. The offering was underwritten by Citigroup Global Markets Inc., J.P. Morgan Securities LLC, and Morgan Stanley & Co. LLC, and several other underwriters.
1. Diamondback Energy, Inc. subsidiary, Viper Energy, Inc., agreed to an all-equity acquisition of Sitio Royalties Corp. for approximately $4.1 billion, including debt, as of June 2, 2025.
2. The Diamondback Stockholders, holding a majority of Viper's voting power, approved the merger agreement on June 2, 2025, via written consent.

3.  The Diamondback Stockholders committed to not selling their Viper stock (or equivalent post-merger) for 90 days after the closing, subject to exceptions, as per a support agreement signed concurrently with the merger agreement.
1. On June 4, 2025, IQVIA Holdings Inc. issued $2,000,000,000 in 6.250% senior notes due 2032.
2. Net proceeds from the note offering will be used to repay existing borrowings and pay fees, with any excess used for general corporate purposes.
3. The Issuer may redeem the notes prior to maturity, subject to a make-whole premium before June 1, 2028, and a declining redemption premium thereafter.
1. Starbucks appointed Mike Grams as COO, increasing his base salary by $200,000 and his annual incentive bonus target to 125% of base salary (effective June 4, 2025).
2. Chief Legal Officer Brad Lerman's departure will result in severance payments calculated according to the company's severance plan.
3.  Starbucks is restructuring to improve performance, though specific numerical targets or timelines are absent from the filing.
1. On June 3, 2025, ONEOK, Inc. completed the acquisition of the remaining 49.9% interest in Delaware G&P LLC for $940 million, becoming the sole owner.
2. The acquisition cost $940 million, comprised of $530 million in cash and $410 million in ONEOK common stock.
3.  The Delaware Basin JV, now wholly owned by ONEOK, has a natural gas processing capacity exceeding 700 million cubic feet per day.

1. Arthur J. Gallagher & Co. held an investor meeting on June 4, 2025,  presenting updated 2025 results estimates, net after-tax cash flow projections from clean energy investments for 2025 and beyond, and including cautionary language about forward-looking statements.
2. The filing is an 8-K, indicating a current report, not a regularly scheduled filing.
3. No specific future impacts or risks with quantifiable numbers were mentioned beyond the cautionary language regarding forward-looking statements.
1. Robert R. Wingo resigned as Executive Vice President Corporate Ventures & Midstream of EQT Corp. effective June 20, 2025, to accept a position at another company.
2.  This 8-K filing, submitted on June 4, 2025, reports an event that occurred on May 30, 2025.
3. No specific future impacts or risks are quantified in this section of the filing.
1. On May 31, 2025, Uber Technologies, Inc. appointed Nikesh Arora to its Board of Directors, adding expertise in technology, finance, and cybersecurity.
2.  Mr. Arora's compensation includes a $60,000 annual cash retainer and an annual restricted stock unit grant valued at $300,000 (prorated for the partial year).
3. Mr. Arora will serve on Uber's Nominating and Governance Committee and Compensation Committee.

1. On May 30, 2025, Rockwell Automation's CEO, Blake D. Moret, established a Rule 10b5-1 trading plan to sell company stock to cover taxes on upcoming restricted stock unit and performance share vesting, and to diversify holdings before stock options expire in 2026.
2. The filing is an 8-K report, indicating other events.
3. No specific future impacts or risks are mentioned beyond the CEO's tax and financial planning, which are normal business activities.

1. Jonathan M. Tisch, Executive Chairman of Loews Hotels Holding Corporation (a Loews Corp subsidiary), will retire on December 31, 2025, and transition to a consulting role for up to 200 hours annually.
2. This filing is an 8-K Current Report, filed on June 4, 2025, regarding a director's departure and officer appointments at Loews Corp.
3.  No specific future financial impacts or risks are detailed in this section of the filing beyond the described personnel changes.
1. Dollar Tree sold its Family Dollar business for $1,007 million, expecting net proceeds of approximately $800 million by the end of the second quarter of fiscal 2025.
2. As of June 4, 2025, Dollar Tree has a $2 million shortfall in letter of credit funds allocated to its supply chain financing program.

3. The $800 million in net proceeds from the Family Dollar sale will be used to reduce supply chain financing program obligations, with the remaining $798 million allocated for general corporate purposes.

1. Old Dominion Freight Line, Inc. reported a 5.8% decrease in revenue per day in May 2025 compared to May 2024, due to lower LTL tons per day, partially offset by increased revenue per hundredweight.
2. Quarter-to-date (as of June 4th, 2025) LTL revenue per hundredweight increased 3.2% year-over-year, while LTL revenue per hundredweight excluding fuel surcharges increased 5.6%.

3.  The company cites continued softness in the domestic economy and lower fuel prices as impacting their May 2025 revenue, while expressing uncertainty about the macroeconomic environment and listing numerous risks in their SEC filing.
1. On June 2, 2025, Andrew Witty's performance-based restricted stock units were cancelled in connection with his retirement from his position as Chief Executive Officer.
2.  At the 2025 Annual Meeting, the shareholder proposal regarding excessive golden parachutes was rejected by a vote of 94,676,898 for and 655,943,208 against.
3.  The 2025 Annual Meeting saw 811,952,044 shares of common stock represented, with various resolutions regarding director elections and executive compensation receiving votes.
1. Dollar Tree sold its Family Dollar business for approximately $1,007 million, expecting net proceeds of $800 million and tax benefits of $350 million, with the sale closing by August 2025.
2.  First-quarter 2025 (ended May 3, 2025) net sales increased by 11.3% to $4.6 billion, driven by higher traffic and average ticket.

3. Dollar Tree anticipates a significant 45-50% year-over-year decrease in adjusted diluted earnings per share for the second quarter of 2025, before a projected recovery in the latter half of the year to reach a full-year target of $5.15 to $5.65 per share.
1.  As of April 30, 2025, four end-users represented 10% or more of the company's financing receivables, totaling 74% of all financing receivables.

2.  The company anticipates $19 million to $26 million in cash expenditures for severance payments and related costs, and $10 million to $20 million in non-cash charges for stock-based compensation, as part of a new strategic plan announced on May 6, 2025.

3. The company is facing several lawsuits related to a July 19, 2024, system crash, including a securities class action lawsuit and consolidated class action lawsuits related to airline flight disruptions,  with unspecified monetary damages sought in each.

1. Gartner Inc.'s 2025 Annual Meeting of Stockholders was held on May 29, 2025, resulting in the election of eleven nominees to the board of directors,  advisory approval of named executive officer compensation, and ratification of KPMG LLP as the independent auditor.
2.  While all board nominees were elected,  support ranged from 56,293,754 votes for William O. Grabe to 66,171,330 votes for Eileen M. Serra, indicating varying levels of shareholder support.
3. No future impacts or risks were explicitly stated in this 8-K filing.

1. Arista Networks, Inc.'s 2025 Annual Meeting on May 30, 2025, resulted in the election of three Class II directors, an advisory approval of named executive officer compensation, and ratification of Ernst & Young LLP as the independent auditor for the fiscal year ending December 31, 2025.
2.  Charles Giancarlo received 656,128,725 "For" votes, Daniel Scheinman received 675,755,003 "For" votes, and Yvonne Wassenaar received 744,203,569 "For" votes in the director elections.
3. The advisory vote on named executive officer compensation resulted in 613,624,231 "For" votes and 374,475,398 "Against" votes.
